<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[94,719,1338,1683]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[94,205,1338,1363]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Remarks:</emphasis>
The new species can be distinguished from all other known 
<taxonomicName box="[284,549,1370,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pseudoptilolepis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[284,458,1370,1395]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Pseudoptilolepis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by the shapes of sternite 5 and cercal plate. It runs to 
<emphasis box="[544,689,1402,1427]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">P. fluminensis</emphasis>
in Couri &amp; Carvalho (2002) key but differs by the abdomen color pattern (
<figureCitation box="[250,311,1466,1491]" captionStart="Figures 1-5" captionStartId="1.[96,164,2074,2099]" captionTargetBox="[94,1389,929,2044]" captionTargetId="figure-276@1.[94,1417,929,2044]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figures 1-5.Pseudoptilolepis puri sp.nov.(1) Head of female,frontal view;(2) Head of male, frontal view;(3) Abdomen of female, dorsal view;(4) Lateral habitus of male;(5) Lateral habitus of female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5235548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5235548/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), by the trapezoidal sternite 5 (
<figureCitation box="[646,707,1466,1491]" captionStart="Figures 6-11" captionStartId="2.[170,238,2074,2099]" captionTargetBox="[176,1493,800,2044]" captionTargetId="figure-259@2.[170,1493,797,2044]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 6-11. Pseudoptilolepis puri sp.nov.(6) Sternite 5; (7) Cercal plate;(8) Aedeagus,lateral right view;(9) Ovipositor,ventral view;(10) Ovipositor,dorsal view; (11) Spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5235550" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5235550/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), as high as wide, with hind margin as an inverted “U” and the shape of the cercal plate (
<figureCitation box="[431,495,1530,1555]" captionStart="Figures 6-11" captionStartId="2.[170,238,2074,2099]" captionTargetBox="[176,1493,800,2044]" captionTargetId="figure-259@2.[170,1493,797,2044]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 6-11. Pseudoptilolepis puri sp.nov.(6) Sternite 5; (7) Cercal plate;(8) Aedeagus,lateral right view;(9) Ovipositor,ventral view;(10) Ovipositor,dorsal view; (11) Spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5235550" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5235550/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). In the other hand, the new species runs to 
<emphasis box="[371,499,1562,1587]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">P. nigripoda</emphasis>
in key of Schühli &amp; Carvalho (2005) although differs by the hind femur yellow and terminalia morphology, especially the cercal plate.
</paragraph>
